b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\r\n<workbook_page xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\r\n\txmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\r\n\txmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\r\n\txmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\r\n\txmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/" id="p6_bohr_calc">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>Bohr Model of the Atom Calculations</title>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="bohr_atom"/>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<p>Bohr postulated that the energy absorbed or emitted when an electron transitioned from\r\n\t\t\tone orbital to another would reflect differences in the orbital energies according to\r\n\t\t\tthis equation:</p>\r\n\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\mid\\Delta E\\mid=\\mid E_f\\;-\\;E_i\\mid$$</formula>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p> Where E <sub>i</sub> is the energy of the electron in its initial orbital and E\r\n\t\t\t<sub>f</sub> is the energy of the electron in its final orbital. Knowing that the\r\n\t\t\tenergies of the orbitals can be calculated with the equation: </p>\r\n\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$E\\;=\\;k\\left(\\frac1{n^2}\\right)$$</formula>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p>These equations can be combined to calculate the change in energy as an electron\r\n\t\t\ttransitions from one orbital to another.</p>\r\n\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\triangle E\\;=\\;k\\;\\left(\\frac1{n_f^2}\\;-\\;\\frac1{n_i^2}\\right)$$</formula>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<p>The wavelength and frequency of the energy absorbed or emitted during this\r\n\t\t\ttransition can also be calculated using the equation:</p>\r\n\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula>$$\\triangle E\\;=\\;h\\nu\\;=\\;\\frac{hc}\\lambda$$</formula>\r\n\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t<example>\r\n\t\t\t<title/>\r\n\t\t\t<p>Calculate the change in energy from the transition of an electron from <em style="italic">n</em> = 3 to <em style="italic">n</em> = 2.\r\n\t\t\t\tWhat is the wavelength of this emission?</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>Using the following equation, we can calculate the energy of the transition:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$\\triangle E\\;=\\;k\\;\\left(\\frac1{n_f^2}\\;-\\;\\frac1{n_i^2}\\right)$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$\\triangle E\\;=\\;-2.18\\times10^{-18}\\;\\mathrm J\\;\\left(\\frac1{(2)^2}\\;-\\;\\frac1{(3)^2}\\right)\\;=\\;-3.03\\times10^{-19}\\;\\mathrm J$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>Note that the negative value of <em style="italic">\xce\x94E</em> indicates an emission of energy.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>Using the following equation we can calculate the wavelength of the energy\r\n\t\t\t\temitted:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$\\triangle E\\;=\\;\\frac{hc}\\lambda$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\lambda\\;=\\;\\frac{(6.626\\times10^{-34}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm J}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm s})(2.998\\times10^8\\;\\mathrm m/\\cancel{\\mathrm s})}{3.03\\times10^{-19}\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm J}}\\;=\\;6.56\\times10^{-7}\\;\\mathrm m\\;=\\;656\\;\\mathrm{nm}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>Notice that this falls within the wavelength range corresponding to red light. It is this transition from\r\n\t\t\t\t<em style="italic">n</em> = 3 to <em style="italic">n</em> = 2 that produces the red line on the line spectra of hydrogen.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<image src="../webcontent/hydrogen_line_spec.png"\r\n\t\t\t\talt="Line spectra of hydrogen showing the red line at approximately 650 nm."\r\n\t\t\t\tstyle="inline" vertical-align="middle" width="600">\r\n\t\t\t\t<caption/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<popout enable="false"/>\r\n\t\t\t</image>\r\n\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="bohr_calc_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t<p>With the puzzling paradoxes of the photoelectric effect and the hydrogen atom now solved\r\n\t\t\tand all involving Planck\xe2\x80\x99s constant in a fundamental manner, it became clear to most\r\n\t\t\tphysicists at that time that the classical theories that worked so well in the\r\n\t\t\tmacroscopic world were fundamentally flawed and could not be extended down into the\r\n\t\t\tmicroscopic domain of atoms and molecules. Unfortunately, despite Bohr\xe2\x80\x99s remarkable\r\n\t\t\tachievement in deriving a theoretical expression for the Rydberg constant, he was unable\r\n\t\t\tto extend his theory to the next simplest atom, He, which only has two electrons. Bohr\xe2\x80\x99s\r\n\t\t\tmodel was severely flawed, since it was still based on the classical mechanics notion of\r\n\t\t\tprecise orbits, a concept that was later found to be untenable in the microscopic\r\n\t\t\tdomain, when a proper model of quantum mechanics was developed to supersede classical\r\n\t\t\tmechanics.</p>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="bohr_calc_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<p/>\r\n\t\t<p/>\r\n\t\t<p> Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\r\n\t\t\ttarget="self" internal="false">Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" target="self" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t\t>Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License</link> . </p>\r\n\t\t<p> Download for free at <link\r\n\t\t\thref="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\r\n\t\t\ttarget="self" internal="false"\r\n\t\t\t>http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312</link> . </p>\r\n\t</body>\r\n</workbook_page>\r\n'